"Today we are fulfilling our manifesto pledge to formally pardon those convicted under historic anti-gay laws.

"It is hugely important that we pardon people convicted of historical sexual offences who would be innocent of any crime today.

"Through pardons and the existing disregard process we will meet our manifesto commitment to put right these wrongs."

status_message:
Read Baroness Nicholson's statement on why she has rejoined the Conservative Party: 

I am rejoining the Conservative Party with tremendous pleasure â coming home to a One Nation party with a drive to deliver for all of Britain.

I'm impressed by Theresa May's ideas and leadership: already laying the foundations for a country that works for everyone; and setting out a proper industrial strategy. In her education speech last week, she showed she leads a party with a real commitment to delivering for the next generation.

I supported Britain's membership of the European Union. But the British people cast a decisive vote and all of us need to deliver on that verdict. I disagreed with the Liberal Democrat leadership â ignoring the vote and continuing with the status quo. So I'm delighted the Tory party is united in its resolve to forge a new role for the UK on the world stage.

Added to this, the Conservative Party in the Lords, with its new leader, is a broad but unified church that understands the purpose of our second chamber: to engage constructively, to scrutinise and revise. Peers should not block the clearly expressed will of the people or the Commons.

I will be fighting for Britain from the Tory benches from now.

Prime Minister Theresa May: "When I talk about a country that works for everyone, it's about ensuring that whatever peoples' talents are, it's about how far their talents can take them... It's ensuring that it is a Government and country that works for everyone."
link_name: A Government and Country That Works for Everyone

The UK oil and gas sector faces real challenges and we are determined to do everything we can to support the industry, and the many jobs which depend on it.

The Scottish Secretary, David Mundell MP, is in to Texas to build links with the US oil industry to help support the UK's oil and gas sector. This relationship-building visit comes after the package of tax measures worth Â£2.3 billion announced in the Budget to support the industry following the fall in the oil price.

It is only because of the broad shoulders of the UK economy that we are able to provide this support to our oil and gas industry, and to the thousands of workers and families it supports, at this very difficult time for the sector.
